## Lessons Learned

- Hydra's `http-post-form` syntax requires inspecting the login request first (DevTools → Network tab) to identify the POST body fields and failure string
- SSH brute-forcing should use `-t 4` to avoid connection errors from rate limiting
- Weak, common passwords (`sunshine`, `butterfly`) appear early in `rockyou.txt` — real targets are found in seconds
- A known username dramatically reduces the search space; username enumeration is often the step before brute-forcing

## Defender's Perspective

- Enforce strong, unique passwords — common passwords are cracked in seconds with rockyou.txt
- Implement account lockout or rate limiting on login endpoints
- Use fail2ban or similar on SSH to block IPs after repeated failures
- Disable password authentication on SSH entirely — use key-based auth only
- Enable MFA on web logins

